John Edwards: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a reputation for academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, only underpinned by individual and collective success in the fields of sport, art, music and other community endeavours.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Independent Schools Council for Scotland (SCIS), seek to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, for the careers they choose and for their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a leading school curriculum, we still see modern languages as popular topics that are chosen in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to someone in a language he understands, that will stay in his memory.
If you talk to someone in their own language, that will stay in your heart."
This is a powerful message to remind us that we can only rely on the English language when we try to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Looking at this year's exam results recently, we can see that languages are at the top of the tables and include the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who studied foreign languages have received a high A grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, shows that 72 per cent of pupils had an A-High in Mandarin, and 72 per cent of those studying German, 69 per cent of those studying French and 63 per cent of those studying Spanish had an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Languages, such as subjects, are now treated in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 per cent of the reasons employers were unable to fill vacancies were due to lack of language skills.
Therefore, there is an increasing demand for languages in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more proposed job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a global environment.
No matter what career one chooses, if that person has learned a second language, he will have a real future advantage in having such a long-term skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people in other countries will mean that a bilingual person will immediately step forward.
According to a YouGov poll involving more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 73 per cent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. In addition, French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of 15 per cent.
This is the reason why investing in language teaching is important to children today.
Being able to speak a number of languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance to find meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages they will teach.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, but other schools will be teaching languages that are considered the most important for the UK when looking around 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a number of languages he can choose from in independent schools, and the schools will include teaching staff specialising in this area.
Scotland's independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will equip children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever is in front of them.
It cannot be denied at present, in a global business environment, that languages are still vital to the country's future, so that must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for Scotland's young people.
It's got to be good to watch.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
