Harvard students are given a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting its undergraduates to sleep more in order to try to tackle the macho culture of studying all night using caffeine.
An academic found that students at the world's best university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of digs after themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital who has designed the course, a course he believes is the first of its kind in the USA.
He was inspired at the start of the course after giving a lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
‘At the end of the lecture a woman came to me and said: ‘Why is it only now that I get to know this, in my last year?’
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleep - it was a surprise to me," he told the Telegraph.
The course, which is being introduced for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how lack of sleep affects athletic performance, and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
‘We are aware that it will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to be told - just as you have a right to be told what the impact of smoking is on your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of being proud to stay up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means that lack of sleep is a problem that is getting worse,
Ensuring you get enough quality, sleep should be a way for students to tackle stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid putting pressure on, because lack of sleep makes the brain believe you're hungry, making you hungry all the time
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having studied one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and was inspired to try to get the course for the whole campus.
It is hoped that the next step will require all postgraduate students to complete a similar study plan before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider setting an alarm for going to sleep, as well as waking up, and be aware of the harmful ‘blue light' effects that are released by electronic screens and LED light, which can affect your circadian rhythm resulting in sleep problems.
